<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,1538]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,323,1191,1217]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Variation:</emphasis>
The male 
<typeStatus box="[451,552,1192,1218]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">paratype</typeStatus>
is 
<quantity box="[587,692,1192,1218]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.13" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="9.13">9.13 mm</quantity>
long. The only variation of note is that front margin of clypeus in this specimen is entirely bright green.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,1538]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,363,1271,1297]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Comparison:</emphasis>
This species superficially resembles the unrelated species 
<taxonomicName authority="LeConte" authorityName="LeConte" box="[1060,1273,1272,1298]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exesa">
<emphasis box="[1060,1160,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">C. exesa</emphasis>
LeConte
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter has the elytra much more coarsely sculptured and with clearly defined, depressed punctured areas, and in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,241,1352,1378]" name="Mexico" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Mexico</collectingCountry>
is known only from Baja California and Sonora. It appears that 
<taxonomicName box="[1029,1176,1352,1377]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tessellata">
<emphasis box="[1029,1176,1352,1377]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">C. tessellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[267,372,1392,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">
<emphasis box="[267,372,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">C. analis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, it bears little resemblance to that species, immediately differing by the patterned elytral sculpturing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,1538]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1471,1497]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name is from the Latin 
<taxonomicName box="[680,802,1472,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tessellatus">
<emphasis box="[680,802,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">tessellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, referring to the vaguely mosaic pattern on the elytral surface.
</paragraph>
